What is the units digit of the product of all the odd positive integers between 10 and 110?
inference:
To find the units digit of the product of all odd positive integers between 10 and 110, we need to find the product of the odd numbers from 11 to 109.
The odd integers are: 11, 13, 15, ..., 109.
We are interested in the units digit of the product.  The units digit of the product will only depend on the units digits of the factors. The units digits of the odd integers from 11 to 109 are 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, repeating every 10 numbers.

The odd integers between 10 and 110 are:
11, 13, 15, ..., 107, 109.
The units digits are: 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, ..., 1, 3, 5, 7, 9
There are $\frac{109-11}{2} + 1 = \frac{98}{2} + 1 = 49 + 1 = 50$ odd numbers.

The units digits are 1, 3, 5, 7, 9. We have 10 of each.
We need the product of these numbers.

11 * 13 * 15 * 17 * ... * 109
Units digits are: 1 * 3 * 5 * 7 * 9 * ... * 9
The pattern of units digits repeats in groups of 10.
Since we have 50 numbers, the units digits are (1)(3)(5)(7)(9) repeated 5 times.
(1)(3)(5)(7)(9) = 945
(1)(3)(5)(7)(9)(1)(3)(5)(7)(9) = 945 * 945 * ....
(1)(3)(5)(7)(9) (1)(3)(5)(7)(9)...
The product of the units digits is 945... the last digit of the product is 5.  (1 * 3 * 5 * 7 * 9 = 945)
Every set of 5 odd numbers has a units digit of 5.  We have 5 sets of 5 odd numbers in our sequence.
50 numbers = 10 groups of 5 odd numbers
So we have 10 groups with units digits of 5.
The product is thus 5 * 5 * 5 * ... * 5 (10 times).
The units digit of the product is 5.

Final Answer: $\boxed{5}$
ground_truth: Any odd multiple of 5 will end in a units digit of 5 (even multiples will end in a units digit of 0). Since all the integers we are multiplying are odd and some of them have a factor of 5, the product will be an odd multiple of 5 with a units digit of $\boxed{5}$.
